      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":13,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (walk/run as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"The entire focus here is tissue tolerance, not fitness. Your foot is still healing, and the goal is to accumulate time on feet at easy effort — 5:58/km or slower — without provoking symptoms. Three runs per week, each capped at 20 minutes. If foot pain or stiffness appears, insert a 2-3 minute walking break immediately rather than stopping the run entirely. Walking breaks are a tool, not a failure. Deload in week 4: reduce to ~8 km to let connective tissue consolidate gains. Progress weekly distance by no more than 10%.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":5,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":14,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":20,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/cross-train or strides (only if cleared)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":344,\"notes\":\"As your foot continues to respond well, run duration can begin creeping toward 25-30 minutes per session — but only with physiotherapist clearance to extend beyond 20 minutes. Weekly volume builds gradually. Cross-training (pool running, cycling) can supplement on non-run days if you want additional aerobic stimulus without foot load. No speed work yet. Deload in week 8 (end of this phase): drop back to ~15 km. The easy pace range opens up slightly — anywhere from 5:24 to 5:58/km is appropriate depending on how your foot feels that day.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":21,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":28,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85/15 easy/moderate (tempo only if cleared by physio)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"This phase introduces a proper long run on Saturdays — starting around 45-50 minutes and building toward 60-70 minutes. Tempo work (4:29/km) may be introduced conservatively — one short tempo segment per week, only after explicit physiotherapist clearance for speed work. If clearance hasn't come, keep all running easy and extend long run duration instead. Deload in week 13: reduce to ~22 km. Your VDOT of 46.5 reflects pre-injury fitness; expect to feel harder effort at paces that once felt comfortable — that's normal and will resolve with consistent training.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":29,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":32,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80/20 easy/hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":324,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"notes\":\"Only enter this phase if your foot has been symptom-free for at least 3-4 consecutive weeks and your physiotherapist has cleared you for full training. This is a brief consolidation block — not a hard push. The long run reaches its peak duration (75-80 minutes). One quality session per week at threshold or interval pace is appropriate. Listen carefully to your foot; any return of plantar fasciitis symptoms means stepping back to the Build phase immediately. This is not a setback — it's smart management.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"A full recovery week to close out the 16-week plan. Three short easy runs, no pressure, no targets. This week is about absorbing everything your body has built over the past 15 weeks. Reflect on how far you've come — from 20-minute walk/run sessions to a rebuilt aerobic base. Use this week to assess where you want to go next: a 10K return-to-race block, a half marathon build, or simply continuing to enjoy consistent, healthy running.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James is returning from active plantar fasciitis with a solid pre-injury fitness base (VDOT 46.5, 44:00 10K) and recent training showing good early progress — three weeks of consistent easy running with only minor, resolving symptoms. That's genuinely encouraging. The plan is structured around one non-negotiable principle: connective tissue heals slower than cardiovascular fitness. The plantar fascia needs graduated mechanical load, not aggressive mileage increases. That's why the first 4 weeks are capped at 20 minutes per run with mandatory walking breaks if any pain appears. The 10% weekly volume rule is strictly observed throughout. Phases progress from pure tissue tolerance (Base) through aerobic rebuilding (Build) to a brief fitness consolidation (Peak), with deload weeks every 3-4 weeks to allow adaptation. Speed work is deliberately excluded until physiotherapist clearance — interval and repetition paces are available in James's fitness profile but would place excessive stress on the plantar fascia before it's ready. The three-days-per-week structure respects James's preference and also provides adequate recovery between sessions, which is especially important for plantar fasciitis management. Saturday long runs are anchored throughout. All easy running targets the slower end of James's easy pace range (5:44-5:58/km) in early phases, with the full range (5:24-5:58/km) opening up as fitness and foot tolerance improve.\",\"warnings\":\"This plan assumes continued physiotherapist oversight throughout. Do not progress beyond Phase 1 (Base) without a follow-up physiotherapist check-in confirming the plantar fasciitis is responding well. Do not introduce tempo or interval work (Phases 3-4) without explicit clearance for speed work. If foot pain returns at any point — especially sharp heel pain in the first steps of a run or after prolonged sitting — stop that session, revert to the previous week's volume, and consult your physiotherapist before resuming. Morning heel pain is a key plantar fasciitis warning sign; do not run through it. Current fitness estimates are based on a pre-injury 10K from September 2025; actual current fitness is likely somewhat lower after the injury layoff, so perceived effort should guide pacing more than target pace numbers in the early weeks.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
